segments.text: Who were some of the memorable teachers, advisors, counselors during your student days?
Well, teachers I remember most was Square Root Jackson.
Describe him, and why did he have that nickname?
Well, he could give you the square of any four-digit number right out of his head.
And he and Dutch Halpern
were retained by one by GE and one by Westinghouse as mathematicians to solve their problems.
They'd send them down here, and sometimes these guys would solve it on the envelope and mail it back to them.
But when we're back to Dutch, I mean, Square Root Jackson, he always rode a bicycle.
And when he would start, he was teaching algebra too.
And when he would start into this and somebody would ask a question, it was not unusual for him to cover up all the blackboards with how you did certain things.
And it had nothing to do with algebra.
He would come in and somebody said, well, he'd ask you to hear something on the radio.
And one time one guy said, no, he said,
I kept getting static because I had a fluorescent lamp and it was giving me static.
I didn't want to turn it out.
So Square Root Jackson goes through the process of how he can stop that.
He came into class one.
We always waited to see if they weren't in class.
Ten minutes after the hour, we walked.
And boy, we just about were out of our seats.
And Square Root walked in and said,
I didn't calculate right on the headwind getting here.
The wind was blowing pretty bad.
Dutch Halpern was another one.
He had a thick brogue.
What did he teach?
He taught algebra.
Somebody asked a question one time.
Math was over on the third floor of the academic building at that time.
And I think everybody in class thought it was a pretty good question.
Dutch walked over there and picked up the book and he said, you don't need the book, and threw it out of the window.
And they made him go down and get it.
And we had a hard time understanding Dutch.
Now, that Dutch was Germanic?
Yeah, he was a Dutchman.
I shouldn't say German.
I mean, he was a Dutchman.
It may have been German, I don't know what we called it in Dutch.
My trig teacher was a gal called... Galdog, what was his name?
Did you say gal?
No, a guy.
Did you have any female instructors at A&M?
Yes.
I had one.
I think it was during a summer session.
I'll come to that when we went to three sessions.
Go ahead.
I had it in the name of my tongue a minute ago.
You'll think of them later.
Anyway, he'd come into class and he did the same damn thing every time he came into class.
He would walk into class, put his stuff down on the little lectern he had,
He'd walk over, regardless of what the weather was, he'd raise the window, and then he'd look out, look both ways.

And then if it was a window, he'd close that window or leave it open, and then he'd come up to the desk, and he would write something on the blackboard, and he'd say, Gentlemen, I'm going to tell you exactly what that means.
God, I can't think of his name.
But he was quite a well-known trig prop.
Then, Screamin' Allen Ellison.
I took two classes.
One of them was not in his class, I was underneath him, in a class underneath him, and taking two classes at once, because the windows were all open, you know.
Then, this was after I came back from the war.
I don't know whether I should give him that or not at this point, but it was,
I just want to tell you that it was after the war we came back and I took English 210, which was argumentative thinking, I believe, and John Paul Abbott taught it.
He was such a dapper fellow and we all liked him very much.
And we had a paper to write one time.
And this was at a time when cold strikes were real big on the East Coast and all that.
And so we had to write something about the cold strikes.
And I wrote two handwritten long pages.
And I had my wife and everybody check it for spelling and punctuation.
And I thought it was letter perfect.
I turned it in.
I got that paper back in it.
and one mark on it, and I had a C. So when the class was over, I went up to him and said, Dr. Abbott, why did you circle this?
There's nothing wrong with the spelling or anything there, and give me a C. He said, you used the word striking personnel, and I think it should have been strikers.
And I said, Dr. Abbott,
It's my paper, I wrote it.
He said, yeah, but I'm the one that graced it.
And you still got a C?
I still got a C on that paper.
And we became very good friends later on after I came to work here.
He was well liked by everybody.
We had, Paul Mason was one in drawing, and then of course I got to go to the industrial education department, Chris Gronemann.
Describe him.
He was a wonderful teacher, and started me, because I quit engineering and went into industrial education, because I knew, it was my background of stuff in spirit, and I knew I couldn't make it.
I had hard enough time with algebra, let alone to go with calculus.
He was a real goodhe kind of convinced me that I ought to walk, because he talked about his high school teaching days back in Oklahoma.
And, of course, we had the machinist
Pop Wagner, and then a guy that taught foundry, and a guy that taught pattern making.
What was it?
Downard.
Downard.
Pop Downard was in the machine shop.
The guy that taught foundry.
Watson?
Watson.
Watson.
Before the war started, what was a typical
days routine for you on a Monday through Friday basis?
What time did you get up and what did you do when?

Well before the war they instituted when we moved over into the new new area they decided we needed to have calisthenics and we resented the heck out of it because we had to get up early in the morning
All of the cadets would go down in a quad, and one of the senior officers would lead us in about 30 minutes to calisthenics.
And we said, we're going to fix them.
We're going to all go to breakfast, and we're just going to eat them out of house and home.
We never made a dent in what they had.
But then we cleaned up our rooms and everything and got ready to go to class.
If we didn't have a class, well, we probably studied.
What time did you get up?

I want to say it was before six o'clock, because I think breakfast was at seven, if I remember correctly, because we marched to all meals in those days, and it was all served family style, and good food, too.
Nobody lost weight.
And we went to class, and we came back, and we
play some kind of a game.
We all, of course, had intramurals.
If it was intramural sports, we entered that.
I was not a wrestler, but they decided I was going to be an entry from B Battery in wrestling one time.
And I'm down at the G Raleigh where I was working.
I was working out, and another guy was working with me, and Marshall Robnett comes in, and he's got a new photographer with him.
And they wanted to get a picture of him refereeing our match.
And it was all posed, and it came out in Life magazine.
I have to tell everybody, I'm the guy on top because you can't see our faces.
Now, you said you marched to every meal.
Did you all march to lunch?
Yes.
And about how much free time did you have between the time you got up in the morning and supper?
Well, it would vary.
We always had a little free time, usually between classes, you know, which might be as much as an hour.
And then we'd usually study or go to the library or go somewhere and get a Coke or something.
And then after supper, we always would go together if the weather was decent.
And we'd have races amongst ourselves, the intramurals.
And they, I can even remember the guys flying kites, you know, and pitching horses.
We didn't pitch, we pitched horseshoes, but that was in PE then, and intramural.
We pitched horseshoes over there.
They had a bunch of horseshoe places.
You probably remember that.
But that was really it.
We didn't have, and then in the evening,
We might go to the movie, maybe the campus theater, but Guyon Hall was a lot cheaper, but first started out at the assembly hall.
And it was very cast-oriented by class members.
Freshmen had certain places to seat, sophomores, juniors, and seniors.
and wrote letters to her girlfriends.
That's what I did a lot of my time was writing divorce letters, trying to make arrangements for a way to go over and see her on the weekend.
How often did you call anybody by telephone long distance in those pre-war years?
Not very often.
I talked to Dolores on a pay phone.
We didn't have telephones in the dorm.
I talked to her, I don't know, maybe once a week.
It didn't cost too much to call.
And sometimes Mother would call, and they'd call me down to the housing office to take this phone call.
And I'd call her collect.
Did you have a personal budget during those years, those pre-war years, of how much spending money you had or anything?
Well, I remember we didn't have very much.
I got a job and was working on a campus at 25 cents an hour.
We'd get paid for that.
When I became a junior and went under contract,
We got $100 a semester, I think it was, or maybe it was $25 a month, I'm not sure.
But that was what our spending money was.
As your years went on, events in Europe and Asia began to be much more important
When did you and your friends start talking about what might be the result of those events in Europe and Asia?
Well, we didn't discuss the war too much in September of 1941.
We knew it was going on, but we didn't talk much about it.
And on December the 7th, I had gone on Saturday the 6th, had gone to Huntsville with a couple of fellows that had a car, and they had arranged dates, and I had a date with a girl.
I went to the, for Sunday, we went to the movie, and when we came back, they went up, a couple of the women went up to their room and got some records, because in the
the lounge there in a women's dormitory, they had a radio and a record player, and we were going to play records and dance a little bit and then go home.
And they came on the radio then, and Pearl Harbor had been bombed.
And then somehow, somebody got the announcement that all A&M cadets report back to the campus immediately.
I don't know how that got on air.
Well, boy, we took off.
I got back on the campus and the freshmen were walking guard duty with brooms and they're shooting the sophomores as spies and the campus was just in upheaval on that Sunday night.
Monday morning, when we started to go to class, I had a portable radio which was about a foot long and you had to plug it in.
And I thought I'd take that to class and we could listen to the news.
And I walked into class and was going to plug it in, and the prof said, well, I haven't got time for that.
The war is going to be over before this semester is over.
You're not going to just forget about that war.
You don't know who that prof was?
No, I wish I could remember who he was, because nobody could have been wronger, of course.
So that's your military science teacher, which Major Bacher was the one that was teaching you military science.
No, that wasn't him.
So you didn't get to hear President Roosevelt's speech to the Joint Session of Congress?
No, I got a record of it, but I didn't hear it.
What did you and your friends then begin to think?
Well, of course, a lot of them were wanting to enlist.
This is in January and so on.
And we played in the Cotton Bowl that year and played Fordham.
But the people at school, the military science teachers and all of the professors and all were urging us not to enlist.
And of course, as soon as you became eligible for a contract, you had to join the ERC, enlisted reserve corps.
And that was trial and error.
There were an awful lot of them that left A&M, and they just couldn't wait to get into the war.
And, of course, the class of 43 that graduated, we went through the trimester, and I'm trying to remember when that was.
Now, your class year is what?
You were class 44.
Because I didn't graduate in 44.
No, no, I understand.
But we went through the trimester thing, and I want to say that we started it in the summer of 43 because I know in the fall I could wear my boots as a senior.
And we had three regular semesters.
They weren't like summer school.
And because of the war, there were a number of changes made in the Corps.
First thing that, excuse me.
Did the Corps become more serious?
Yeah, it was always pretty serious.
The seniors ran the outfits, the juniors were the NCOs, the sophomores were the corporals if there was enough stripes to go around.
But the first thing that happened when I was a junior, up until that point, seniors and juniors wore cuffs on their long trousers.
Well, they took the cuffs away when I became a junior, and I never got to wear cuffs.
And seniors wore a Sam Brown belt and a long blue coat and boots.
Well, I got to be a senior, and I'd already bought a pair of secondhand boots.
They did away with boots and the sand brown and the saber.
That wasn't in the Army, so they gave us blouses with a cloth belt on it.
But I wore those boots.
When I'd leave the campus, I'd put on white coveralls.
That was all fatigues, was white coveralls.
I'd get out on the road, and I'd get away from the campus and take them off, and I'd hitchhike.
You leave A&M when?
Well, let's see.
The class of 44 and 45 all went in at the same time, and I guess that must have been
In 43, I think it was, we had three reviews.
44 took them around, 45 took them around, 46 took them around.
And when the last group came around, they were just squads.
Did you and your friends ever lie awake at night talking about where you might be sent, what it might
how your life might be affected?
Well, we all, we talked about what we, you know, what we, of course, see, my group all had to go to OCS.
And we wondered sometimes how, you know, how that was going to be.
And, yeah, we wondered about where we were going to go and what the war was going to be.
And Dolores and I talk about it, and she was worried, too, even though we weren't married at that time.
Well, you went to Mineral Wells when you were inducted there.
Yeah, I went to Mineral Wells.
So you were at Camp Walters, you were inducted.
Yeah, and then came back to A&M.
Oh.
And how long?
The whole outfit was private.
They put you in ASTP.
And how long were you here in the ASTP?
Well, we were in there until the end of that semester.
Then we went to...
My group went to San Antonio, Fort Sam Houston.
From there, they broke us down and I wound up at Fort Sill, Oklahoma, because I was in the artillery.
And I didn't go to OCS.
I went to a battery survey school.
Then they sent us back to A&M, and that's when we was in the ASTP.
So now this was in the late 43 or the early part of 44, I guess, because we left here.
and went to OCS at Fort Sill, Oklahoma.
Second week I was there, my class and the class behind me were taking out, and some of us went to infantry and some went to armor.
I started infantry OCS on D-Day, 1944.
How well did A&M prepare you for duty?
Very well, very well.
We knew two things.
We knew how to study, and we at least knew a right foot from a left foot, and we could march.
And if we got in charge of a group, we could move them from one place to the other.
And we knew about weapons to a degree.
And we were used to being with people and close with people.
that a lot of guys in the Army had a little trouble with.
So that, we got married before I went to, when I went up to Ford's Hill, didn't I?
They got married at the,
Methodist Parsons in College Station, and I got a three-day pass.
We spent our honeymoon in the LaSalle Hotel, and then I had to move out of that.
She stayed over here as long as I was here.
Moved into Aggieland Inn, didn't I?
Yeah, out of the room.
Before I could get to Fort Sill, you were sent to Fort Benning.
While you were on active duty, do you think
officers from other places had a respect for A&M people?
All except, we call them the ring knockers, the guys from West Point.
They would always, they'd kind of look down and, oh, any ROTC thing.
Oh, I see.
But a lot of the others that came, see, they had ROTC, but they didn't have the core like we had it.
And, uh,
Yeah, they had respect for it.
And, of course, we'd always see an officer when we were in OCS and before, and then even after we got commissioned to see if they wore an Aggie ring.
You weren't yet a senior.
You didn't have a ring when you left, or did you?
Yes.
Oh, you did.
Got a ring.
Do you remember any anecdotes about somebody spotting your ring while you were on active duty?
Oh, yes.
I can remember, you know, are you an Aggie?
What class are you?
And we'd go through that.
We got a ring and it cost me $50 then.
And it was the first ones that Bob Ford made that had a curved crown.
It had too much gold in it, it wore off.
Tell us about the Aggies.
They were standing on the street corner
Oh, well, I'm coming to that.
And she can tell you about an Aggie that picked her up when she was coming to California to see me.
We were at the Camp Van Dorn.
Van Dorn?
It was at, what was the camp at Hattiesburg?
Shelby.
Shelby at Hattiesburg.
And I was in the 49th Infantry, 149th Infantry Regiment.
And it was muster.
So my roommate, Dick Phillips, and I decided we might just kind of get together.
And so Dolores and I had gone into town, into town, into downtown Hattiesburg.
and was walking down the street.
I was going to buy some socks, and we were going to go to the grocery store, and a guy walks up to me and slaps me on the shoulder, and he said, is that an Aggie ring?
And I said, yes, it is, and he showed me his ring, and that was Ed Glazner, wasn't it?
It was Emmett McLarty.
McLarty.
He said, I'd always been told if you stood on a street corner anywhere in the world long enough, an Aggie would walk by.
My friend over across the street, he's waiting over there, and he waited to come over.
They said, where's the muster?
I said, as far as I know, my roommate and I are the only two Aggies on the post.
So I said, we'll just have a dinner at our house, and we'll have a muster at our house.
And this was before the days where they had candles and some of that.
But they said, well, we've got some stamps for meat.
So we went to the market, and Dolores bought, what was it, did you buy a roast or steak?
Steaks.
Steaks.
Now, we've got a room...
Dolores was real smart about this.
She always said, you can live just as cheap in the silk stocking area as you can in the slums if you're going to rent a room.
So she had gone in the best area of Hattiesburg.
I'll tell you the story about that woman.
Well, I went down the street, and the biggest house, the finest house I saw rang the doorbell.
And this woman comes to the door.
And she, we got to talking, and she said, you're a southerner, aren't you?
And I said, yes, I am.
I'm from Texas.
Well, she pulled me inside.
They just treated us like we were one of theirs.
We had a room and a bath, and we had privileges to the whole house.
And to the kitchen, probably.
So Emmett McLarty and Everett Glazner thought that...
So we had the dinner, and...
They thought that was my house.
They'd go home and they'd tell their wives that they had met this rich Aggie.
And they never invited us to their home.
We found out 25 years later that the reason they never had had the then was because they thought their houses were so crummy.
And I said, oh Lord, we just had a roof.
Back to Muster.
Do you remember going to Muster on campus before you left for the service?
No.
So that muster began to mean something to you when you were away.
Yeah, yeah.
I just don't remember a muster on campus.
I haven't talked to many people who do remember pre-World War II musters.
That's right.
But it started during the war.
Most of them say, I think maybe muster was held, but I'm not sure on campus.
And yet they held a muster on Corregidor just before it fell in 1942.
We had one on Okinawa, because I was there on the 21st, and they had them all over.
Let's go back just a second on muster and other.
Midnight yell practice before the war, were there midnight yell practices?
Yes.
Where were they described?
All Yale practice started out on the steps of the Y, and we got to the big, that they moved it over to the steps on Goodman Hall that faced the Koch building.
The entrance to the Goodman.
Mitchell was a dormitory on the other side.
They tore it down.
And we had it there, and the band and all came, and midnight Yale practice was
People came in uniforms and a bonfire uniform.
And as I told you, if we had a date and there was a dance, the gals came in their long dresses.
And they had some, the yard leaders all had little stories to tell, but they were,
I mean, way milder than what you hear now.
There was very little vulgarity.
Maybe they were to hell or damn, but that was about it.
All right.
Bonfire.
Describe pre-World War II bonfires.
Well, the first one I went to was across the street on the drill field from Law and Puryear.

Southern Pacific and Missouri Pacific Railroad would always bring in, before Thanksgiving, they'd bring in extra baggage carts, which were four-wheeled carts with a tongue on it, because they knew we were going to come down there and get them.
And so after they began to bring them in, we'd always leave one so the train could have it.
And that's how we hauled stuff to the bonfire.
It was really almost like a big trash fire.
And, of course, we had anywhere, most I ever remember, I think, was four outhouses, but maybe two to four outhouses on there.
And you could set it on fire pretty easy.
And, of course, the cavalry lived in Long Perrier.
and they had an old claxton.
If they thought somebody was coming in and they drank that claxton boy, they'd fall out of there anyway.
Now, Art, so the bonfire basically was trash.
Well, it was just scrub lumber and trees.
But it wasn't all tree trunks.
No.
And where did the outhouses come from?
wherever we could get them.
And of course, they always, we tried because the university would have to build them a new one.
Most of the time it was from some, I guess,
